I created the storyboards for our phishing awareness game using possible realistic university student situations.
The aim of the storyboards is to teach players how to identify phishing attacks and how to deal with them while keeping the learning interesting.
In Storyboard 1, I created all the scenarios based on Coventry university.First an urgent assignment re-upload scam where the player receives a fake Turnitin email stating that the submission failed and threatens to give the student zero marks if not re uploaded immediately..
This scenario teaches students how attackers create urgent situations, fear, fake university emails, and fake links to steal students login credentials.
In Storyboard 2, I designed a fake IT support password reset scam where the player receives an email stating  their university password will expire today and if not changed within 3 hours it threatens to suspend student's email account.
This storyboard teaches students how to identify fake password reset links, suspicious domains, and the importance of verifying unauthorized requests with the help of official university channels.
In Storyboard 3, I created a fake tuition fee refund scam where the student receives an SMS claiming they are eligible for a tuition refund as due to some technical issue they payed the amount twice.
This scenario teaches players how scammers use financial pressure, excitement, urgency, and fake refund links to steal banking details.
In all three storyboards mentioned above, I included the character, problem, mission, challenge, player choices, feedback with addition and subtraction of points according to choices made, results, and learning objectives.
I designed the storyboards to make the game educational, interactive, realistic, and suitable for university students.
